A comparison of Clinton&#39;s and Trump&#39;s economic policies: It&#39;s all about the money
Invest in infrastructure and prevent the TTP trade agreement - that&#39;s what both Clinton and Trump want.
However, the two US presidential candidates disagree on tax and energy policy and on a fundamental issue.
Underlying the differences in economic policy between Donald Trump and Hillary Clinton is a fundamental, more philosophical difference.
The one about the role of the state.
Trump wants to keep it small when in doubt and warns of how the state can damage the economy - with taxes and regulations.
Clinton wants to tax the economy to death and regulate it to death, he says.
He himself, on the other hand, would be very different, Trump claims.
He will massively reduce regulations, and he is campaigning for far-reaching tax reform with lower tax rates - for private individuals and companies.
Clinton, on the other hand, says: The state has certain tasks to fulfill, it has to open up opportunities for the disadvantaged and needs money for this.
That&#39;s why taxes for the rich would be increased, she says.
Interestingly, both are very close when it comes to infrastructure.
It must be invested in, say Trump and Clinton almost word for word.
The democratic candidate even announces the largest investment in new jobs since the Second World War.
State investment programs in infrastructure are classic democratic politics and are strictly rejected by the state-critical tea party wing of the Republicans.
Internal party discussions could therefore still come to Trump.
The differences in energy and climate policy are clearer.
Trump wants to build coal-fired power plants and ramp up coal production in the US again.
Oil production should also be possible in previously protected areas, and he wants to cancel the Paris climate protection agreement.
Clinton, on the other hand, wants to expand renewable energies with her investment program and demands: &quot;One country will become the superpower of clean energies and create millions of jobs.&quot;
&quot;It will probably be either China, Germany or America - I want it to be us.&quot;
But not only in terms of infrastructure - the two competitors are also not too far apart when it comes to international trade agreements.
Neither want to sign the TPP, the transpacific trade agreement.
At the same time, neither of them want to isolate the United States from international trade - they just want to better protect American jobs.
They should then also be better paid, demands Clinton, for example.
The current minimum wage of $7.25 is a starvation wage.
She wants to raise it to $15 an hour.
It&#39;s not entirely clear what Trump wants to do on this issue: once he says: The minimum wage has to go up, then he says it shouldn&#39;t be changed.
But the major discussion in the coming months is more likely to focus on the tax policies of the two camps.
On one side is Trump, who wants to unburden the economy and citizens in order to boost growth.
His critics accuse him of only widening the budget deficit.
On the other side is Clinton, who wants to demand at least that the rich pay more taxes, and her critics say: More taxes are not the solution either.
Escape: &quot;Every refugee woman has experienced sexual violence&quot;
Sexual violence is almost part of everyday life for women who flee alone.
When they arrive in Germany, they are often traumatized.
A house offers shelter.
Four women are sitting in a large kitchen.
Each has a baby with them that is no more than one year old.
One put her little son in her arms.
He looks curiously into the room with wide eyes.
His mother stares at the tabletop.
Until she realizes she&#39;s being watched.
She smiles briefly and kisses the little one.
The scene looks normal.
Until you speak to Katrin Bahr.
She is the division manager of Condrobs, a provider of social assistance in Bavaria, and deals with the issue of women fleeing, among other things.
The four women in the kitchen are refugees.
They live in the north of Munich in one of the few decentralized accommodations for women who have fled alone and their children in Bavaria.
In January, Condrobs opened the facility together with Pro Familia and the Munich Women&#39;s Aid.
It was recently officially opened.
60 people live there - about 40 women and 20 children.
There are no men - not even as visitors.
The exception is a security guard in front of the door.
&quot;It&#39;s no exaggeration to say that every woman who arrives here has experienced sexual violence while fleeing,&quot; says Bahr.
&quot;Men flee because of wars, because they are politically persecuted, because they are threatened with torture or death, or because their families send them to Europe as beacons of hope,&quot; she says.
Other reasons for fleeing predominate among women: &quot;Many sneak away secretly because they don&#39;t see any other way out.&quot;
In their homeland they have experienced sexual violence, forced marriages, honor killings, slavery or forced prostitution.
That drives her on.
This continues on the run.
&quot;It&#39;s not uncommon for traffickers to ask for a sexual act in exchange for a bottle of water,&quot; says Bahr.
And the women are alone, they are not protected by their families.
Anyone who thinks that the end as soon as they arrive in Germany is wrong, says Bahr.
Here, too, single women in refugee shelters are often viewed as inferior and, in the worst case, abused.
As a result, she estimates that around 90 percent of the women who live in the accommodation in the north of Munich are traumatized.
&quot;Some of the children certainly didn&#39;t come about voluntarily.&quot;
Many women are so used to not saying anything.
&quot;Or they don&#39;t dare to speak openly about what they&#39;ve experienced because they&#39;re too ashamed.&quot;
Since they often do not know what to do, Bahr demands that more accommodation be provided just for them.
In Bavaria, the seven district governments are responsible for housing refugees.
When asked if they knew of a project similar to the one in Munich in their area of responsibility, some answered no.
In the Upper Palatinate and Upper Franconia, for example, there is no such thing in government accommodation.
Even in Swabia, women who have fled alone are not accommodated separately, says Karl-Heinz Meyer, the government&#39;s press spokesman.
In Upper Bavaria, Lower and Middle Franconia, there are floors or separate houses only for single women and their children in some communal accommodations.
The exception is Lower Bavaria, where there are two central accommodations exclusively for women.
The Committee on Women&#39;s Rights and Gender Equality in the European Parliament is also calling for women to be accommodated separately from men.
According to a study published for the committee, &quot;It is very important that men and women are housed separately.&quot;
&quot;If there is a lack of privacy or if men and women are housed together, there can be - ongoing - violence against women&quot;.
The washrooms in particular should be separate and easily accessible for women, according to the study.
How much the women feel this need for protection can be seen from the rush to the house in Munich.
&quot;Since word got around that we exist, we&#39;ve had a long waiting list,&quot; says Bahr.
You could easily open a second house.
