Russia and Türkiye: An &quot;Alliance of Outsiders&quot;?
It was a gesture that ended a crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and announce an official end to the eight-month war of words and economic sanctions.
But as Vladimir Putin welcomes his Turkish opponent in the Gilded Hall of the St. Petersburg Palace, I cannot help but get the impression that Ankara wants this reconciliation the most.
There was the handshake, yes.
But Putin&#39;s smile was tight-lipped and he barely exuded warmth, even by his reserved standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, spoke repeatedly of his &quot;dear friend&quot; Putin - according to one report, a total of five times.
I couldn&#39;t count anymore.
He also promised that relations with Russia would not only return to their pre-crisis levels, but would even improve.
The next day, a newspaper reported that Erdogan behaved as if nothing bad had ever happened.
His enthusiasm seemed to me to indicate the opposite.
But a sustained coolness radiating from Putin showed that the Russian head of state had forgotten nothing.
Rather, the cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his introductory remarks: Turkey shooting down a Russian warplane on the Syrian border.
Moscow&#39;s reaction at the time was furious.
Putin lashed out, accusing Ankara of stabbing Russia in the back.
The offense was even greater since it was committed by an assumed friend.
Rebuilding trust will be difficult, if not impossible.
Public opinion in Russia has changed since November.
For months, the state-controlled media launched a violent, all-out assault on Ankara.
Suddenly it seemed that the Turks were to blame for everything.
Most serious were allegations by senior officials that Erdogan&#39;s own family had benefited from illegal oil trade in areas of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He has vehemently denied this.
But in St. Petersburg, the official message was that it was time to look ahead.
After all, this meeting only took place because Putin received the apology he wanted to hear from President Erdogan.
Russia was able to record a kind of victory.
For Ankara, the benefits of a ceasefire are obvious.
First and foremost, Erdogan needs all the friends he can get after he was nearly impeached in a failed coup last month.
Repeated terrorist attacks on Turkey have also shaken him.
But there are also economic motives.
Russian sanctions have hit Turkey hard -- particularly the ban on charter flights, which typically bring tens of millions of Russian tourists to Turkey&#39;s shores each year.
The number has decreased by almost 90%.
In Russia, tour operators and charter companies will be relieved when flights resume.
They are counting on a late-season rush to the Mediterranean.
This week, state television forecast cheaper fruit and vegetables once Turkey&#39;s agricultural imports are allowed again.
A report in Vedemosti put it this way: &quot;Tourists this way, tomatoes this way.&quot;
But the visit had additional political value for Moscow.
Ankara is furious with the West, considering its response to the attempted takeover as a weak response.
Add to that lingering resentment at the snail&#39;s pace of EU accession negotiations and Putin - who is keen to capitalize on the cool mood and dilute Turkey&#39;s relationship with the West.
The Russian leader certainly won a bonus in Ankara for calling for support for elected officials after the attempted coup.
Mind you, this is a matter of course for Moscow, which itself has a deep-seated fear of regime change.
The summit meeting in this glamorous seaside palace enabled Russia and Turkey to portray what one analyst once described to me as an &quot;alliance of misfits&quot;: two countries, rejected and mistreated by the West, who are now joining forces.
However, despite the public reconciliation, major differences still exist between the two.
The biggest difference is Syria, where Moscow recently gave itself the role of peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey support opposing sides.
It might be significant that after almost three hours of initial talks, both presidents testified at the press conference that they had not even touched on the subject.
Turkey&#39;s President purposely avoided answering a question about their differences, while Putin chose to emphasize it.
There is no clear consensus on where a common denominator can be found on Syria.
But after months of open hostilities -- and given the potential for complete disaster when NATO member Turkey shot down the Russian fighter jet -- it&#39;s certainly better that the two leaders at least talk to each other again.
