Singing often has a very special effect on older people, says Ursula Lenz from the Federal Association of Senior Citizens&#39; Organisations.
In the older generations, singing together was much more important, it was part of everyday life, both at school and in our free time, she explains.
Lenz often observes that singing or listening to songs in older people brings back many memories, often linked to positive feelings from their youth.
Through lyrics and especially melodies, even people with dementia can remember events that happened a long time ago.
Singing also demands a special performance from the head, explains Lenz.
Concentrating on your own voice and on a given rhythm at the same time while adapting to the other singers - that is a great cognitive challenge.
Older people in particular who live alone practice not only concentrating on themselves.
Another positive aspect is the recognition one gets from singing in a choir, says Hackler.
An enthusiastic audience is great praise.
Singing in a choir also increases self-esteem.
