Although trampolining has been an Olympic event since 2000, when it made its debut in Sydney, it has received so little attention over the past 16 years that many I interviewed were unaware that it was an Olympic sport at all.
That could also be regional ignorance.
Although the USA sent athletes to compete, it has never won a trampoline medal and until 2012 had one athlete make it to the finals.
The Chinese and Russians tend to share prices for men and the Chinese and Canadians for women.
Dong Dong from China and Rosie MacLennan from Canada will defend their gold medal from London this year.
Trampolining has a certain outsider charm, partly because, to the unenlightened ear, it sounds more appropriate for clown school than for the Olympics.
At this point, I should admit that I&#39;m no expert, just an earthbound enthusiast.
It has humorous potential - the cartoonish tremors of its never-ending impact - but also the grace of gymnastics and diving, the two sports it essentially unites.
The word &quot;trampoline&quot; comes from the Spanish el trampoline, which means &quot;springboard.&quot;
Aspiring winners jump on a giant trampoline, rocketing nearly 30 feet into the air and must complete a series of falling moves (spins, dives, and somersaults) before landing on their feet.
According to the official Olympic program, they are evaluated according to execution, degree of difficulty and &quot;flight time&quot;.
Thirty-two athletes from 17 countries, 16 men and 16 women, will compete in Rio.
The most common Olympic vector is straight.
Medal hopefuls must go further, faster, up and over, sometimes to the finish line, sometimes back and forth, up and down the playground in their pursuit of gold.
Not only are they chasing the finish line or the exit wall, they are also chasing another taunting target on TV: that of the world or the Olympic record.
The single-minded pursuit is noble, admirable, even fanatical - and it&#39;s enough to bring even a viewer to tears.
But it&#39;s also what I find a little tiring even while watching these games.
The trampoline offers a respite from this.
Trampoline jumper vector is up.
Forward movement is not the goal.
He or she bounces off, seemingly weightless like an astronaut, going up, then down, then effortlessly back up.
There is competition here too, not without difficulty, of course, but during the exercise there is no frantic attack on the target, no arching into the distance, just the dreamy, elegant suspension of time and gravity.
It&#39;s as Zen as competition at the Olympics can get.
