NBC will air the finals as part of an afternoon block beginning at 2 p.m. both days.
In the midst of the Olympic mania, they promise a quiet, nice moment, one that&#39;s likely to be overlooked in the general hubbub.
If awareness raising can only be achieved by ogling and objectifying male athletes - as US male gymnasts recently suggested, according to The Wall Street Journal - then Mr. Dooley awaits his gasping new fanbase.
&quot;A generation protests&quot; in Ethiopia, Long a US ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia have met violent opposition from the government.
Witnesses say dozens of protesters were killed in gunfire during clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia about to collapse?
Over the past decade it has been one of Africa&#39;s most stable countries, a solid ally of the West with a fast-growing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have shaken the country and spread to more and more areas.
Last week thousands of people took to the streets demanding fundamental political changes.
The government&#39;s response was ruthless, according to human rights organizations.
Witnesses said police shot and killed scores of unarmed demonstrators.
Videos circulating about the protests, believed to be from last year or early this year, show security guards beating young people with sticks while they were being forced to do a handstand against a wall.
The head of the UN agency for human rights is now demanding an in-depth investigation.
&quot;It has always been difficult to keep this country together and it will be even more difficult in the future,&quot; said Rashid Abdi, the Horn of Africa project leader of the International Crisis Group, a research group.
Ethiopia is the most populous country in Africa after Nigeria and its stability is valued by the West.
American military and intelligence agencies are working closely with the Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats beyond the region, particularly in Somalia. Few countries, if any, in Africa receive as much Western aid.
Ethiopia&#39;s economy expanded at a remarkable pace.
Its infrastructure has improved drastically - there is a new commuter train in the capital, Addis Ababa.
The streets are generally quiet, safe and clean.
Although Ethiopia has been far from a model of democracy - human rights organizations have consistently cited the government&#39;s repression - opposition in the country has been curbed, with dissidents effectively silenced.
Many were exiled, imprisoned, killed, or driven into the vast wilderness.
But that could change.
&quot;When you suppress people and they have no other option but to protest, it erupts,&quot; said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer in central Ethiopia.
All youth protested.
A generation protests.
Complaints abound, covering everything from land use to a stranglehold on the ruling coalition&#39;s power.
After a widely criticized election last year, the ruling party and its allies won the opposition&#39;s last seat and now control 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, tensions are rising along the border with Eritrea; a fight over that jagged, controversial line claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatists like the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, who have been more or less defeated in recent years, could take advantage of the turmoil and rearm.
Several factors explain why feelings of resentment are exploding beneath the surface after years of simmering.
The first seems harmless: smartphones.
Only in recent years have many Ethiopians been able to communicate through social media as cheaper smartphones became more common and internet services improved.
Even if the government blocks access to Facebook and Twitter, which it does on a regular basis, especially during protests, many people can still communicate through internet proxies that hide their whereabouts.
Several young Ethiopians said they gathered this way to protest.
The second factor is that there is more solidarity between the Oromos and Amharas, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
The Oromos and Amharas are not natural enemies.
For eons, the Amharas, who come from Ethiopia&#39;s predominantly Christian highlands, have prospered in politics and economy while exploiting the Oromos, many of whom are Muslim and live in lowland areas.
But that too is changing.
&quot;We are in the process of coordinating under one umbrella,&quot; said Mulatu Gemechu, an Oromos leader.
The largest protests took place in Amhara and Oromo areas.
Many Amharas and Oromos feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, who make up around 6 percent of the population and are dominant in the military, intelligence, trade and politics.
The third reason for the riots is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Mr. Meles, a former rebel leader, was Ethiopia&#39;s prime minister for 17 years until his death from an undisclosed illness in 2012.
He was seen as a tactical genius, a man who could think outside the box.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at spotting early signs of dissatisfaction and using special envoys to process opponents and render them harmless.
&quot;The current regime lacks these basic skills,&quot; said Mr. Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia&#39;s new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, was chosen to take Mr Meles&#39; position for relatively obscure reasons.
Unlike Mr. Meles who was from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Mr. Hailemariam is from the south.
Analysts say he is not trusted by the Tigray-controlled security services.
Many fear the result will be more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia saw such an uproar was in 2005, after thousands protested elections that analysts say appeared to have been botched and subsequently stolen by the government.
During the raids that followed, many protesters were killed, albeit fewer than in previous months, and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts hailed Ethiopia&#39;s leaders for their visionary infrastructure planning, like the new commuter train, as well as for their measurable progress in reducing poverty.
But apparently this has not prevented the intensification of the Ethiopian government&#39;s internal grudges.
And it takes on a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, an Amharic city, attacked Tigray-run businesses and hatred of the Tigray is becoming more common on social media.
Analysts say the protests put the US and other Western allies in an odd position.
The US government used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced that it had closed the base.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, it doesn&#39;t want its ally to collapse in an already volatile area.
&quot;This,&quot; said Mr. Abdi, &quot;is a very thin line to walk.&quot;
