The Depressing Eating of the Depression in &quot;One Hearty Meal&quot;
In March 1933, shortly after his ascension to the presidency, Franklin Delano Roosevelt lunched in the Oval Office.
A foodie, President Roosevelt had a thing for refined Fifth Avenue delicacies like pâte de foie gras and Maryland turtle soup.
His menu that day was a bit more modest: stuffed eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes and a plum pudding for dessert.
&quot;It was an act of culinary solidarity with people who are suffering,&quot; said Jane Ziegelman.
Her husband Andrew Coe added, &quot;It was also a message to Americans about how to eat.&quot;
The couple live in Brooklyn Heights and are both food historians.
Coe&#39;s latest book, Chop Suey, was about Chinese cuisine in the United States, while Ziegelman&#39;s book, 97 Orchard, is about life in a Lower East Side apartment building from a food perspective.
Her latest collaboration, A Decent Meal, due out Tuesday from Harper Publishing, chronicles the history of American cuisine during the Great Depression.
They showed culinary solidarity when they met a reporter for dinner at Eisenberg&#39;s Sandwich Shop, a small, no-frills eatery in the Flatiron District that&#39;s been in business since the 1929 stock market crash.
Ziegelman, 54, ordered a cream cheese sandwich with diced olives, while Coe, 57, ate turkey with mashed potatoes and mixed vegetables.
When the reporter ordered meatloaf, the couple thought it was fitting for a discussion about food in the Great Depression era.
&quot;Rich foods were very popular,&quot; said Ziegelman.
There was peanut bread, meat loaf and bean bread.
They were made from an ingredient and something cheap that stretches the ingredient.
Imagine eating so many peanuts that they serve as dinner.
Coe grinned.
&quot;It must have settled like lead in the stomach,&quot; he said.
In the years leading up to the Great Depression, the table in an American household, especially in rural areas, was an all-you-can-eat buffet.
Crews of women cooked for male field workers and freshly baked pie was served for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
It was the Americans who sent food to starving Europeans during World War I. &quot;A Square Meal&quot; chronicles the ways in which the country dealt with no longer being the Land of Cockaigne.
&quot;It was a time when food became a hot topic for Americans,&quot; Coe said, explaining why he and his wife wanted to write about it.
Equally tense was the new budget diet: Mysterious foods like breads and casseroles became staples, the casserole a &quot;wonderful way to recycle leftovers,&quot; noted Ziegelman, as cooks could hide unsavory ingredients under a creamy sauce.
Fresh fruit has been replaced with cheaper dried fruit.
Meat, which for years was the focal point of American cuisine, became a rarely served luxury.
Odd concoctions were tried, as high-calorie and nutritious satisfaction took precedence over taste or even common sense.
During her research for the book, which also includes recipes, Ziegelman prepared a dish from that era, baked onions with peanut butter.
&quot;It wasn&#39;t a popular lunchtime addition,&quot; says Coe.
Ziegelmann continues: &quot;It was surreal.&quot;
Peanut butter and baked onions don&#39;t mix.
It was typical of many of the housekeeping recipes.
As never before or since, home economists - including Louise Stanley, head of the Federal Bureau of Home Economics from 1923 to 1943 - so fueled the country&#39;s eating habits.
By publishing recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines, they encouraged women to become &quot;household politicians&quot; and rise to the challenge of turning goo like creamy spaghetti with carrots into delicious meals.
&quot;A Square Meal&quot; is a celebration of historical goodies.
Particularly palatable are the accounts of the government&#39;s response to starving citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover&#39;s let-me-eat-cake attitude.
While publicly praising his kitchen&#39;s simple Iowa farmhouse fare, he ate like the millionaire man of the world he has become.
&quot;He liked continental cuisine like fish with pickle sauce,&quot; said Coe.
He ate in an almost gilded dining room and wore a tuxedo.
He was delightfully out of touch with reality.
President Roosevelt might have made the same mistake if his wife Eleanor hadn&#39;t encouraged him to make an example with his stomach.
As described in the book, Ms. Roosevelt&#39;s hiring of a housekeeper with no interest in flavors resulted in the White House producing the most boring food in Washington, but also one of the most dismal prepared ones.&quot;
Many of the Depression-era ways of dealing with food were discarded once the country got back on its feet.
The legacy lies in our continued focus on calories and nutrition, said Ziegelman, and how science has been applied to food.
While writing the book, the couple said they gained a better understanding of Ziegelman&#39;s mother-in-law&#39;s eating habits - like how she couldn&#39;t throw away food.
&quot;She had a real fear of food waste,&quot; Coe said.
Ziegelman recalled, &quot;She actually made people sick.&quot;
Then there was the windbag incident.
After the plates were cleared at Eisenberg&#39;s, she and Coe pulled out a dessert they had made at home: the plum dessert that President Roosevelt had for lunch.
&quot;It&#39;s called Prune Whip,&quot; said Ziegelman, adding that giving humble recipes a fancy name was a common ploy.
There was no whipped cream, just prunes, some flour, sugar, water and cinnamon.
Each reluctantly dipped a spoon into the chewy brown goo.
Amazingly, it didn&#39;t taste bad.
Coe grabbed a second helping three times.
Like a can-do budgeter, he told his wife, &quot;A few chopped walnuts would help.&quot;
