Greenland Shark: The oldest vertebrate is almost 400 years old
Rare sight.
Greenland sharks usually only come to the surface in winter.
This shark was allowed back into the sea after being examined aboard the research vessel Sanna.
He was born in 1624 and swims through the North Atlantic at a good 1 km/h - to this day.
Greenland sharks don&#39;t give birth until they are 150 years old.
The Greenland shark swims leisurely along the bottom of the North Atlantic, covering an average distance of just 1,220 meters in an hour.
Only when it really matters does the five-meter-long animal accelerate to a whopping 2.6 km/h - and at this top speed is half as fast as a seal.
However, this slow-moving lifestyle seems to be a panacea for old age.
In any case, Julius Nielsen from the University of Copenhagen and his colleagues report in the journal Science about a Greenland shark that could be 392 years old.
&quot;Incredible,&quot; says Alexander Scheuerlein from the Max Planck Institute for Demographic Research in Rostock, commenting on this lifespan, which is a world record for vertebrates.
The evolutionary biologist had suspected for a long time that Greenland sharks lived to be very old.
Only the evidence was missing.
Greenland sharks are difficult to observe, after all they live mainly in the Arctic Ocean off the sparsely populated coasts of Canada, Greenland, Norway and Spitsbergen.
Because they prefer water temperatures around six degrees Celsius, they usually only appear on the surface in winter.
Accordingly, researchers know little about the lifestyle of Greenland sharks.
They measured their slow-motion speed when they equipped six animals with a transmitter off Spitsbergen.
These sharks still make prey: researchers found the remains of a seal in one animal&#39;s stomach, while another had swallowed the jawbone of a young polar bear.
They may hunt sleeping animals or patrol the bottom of the Arctic Sea, looking for carcasses that stagger down from higher water levels.
Julius Nielsen and his colleagues have now examined 28 Greenland sharks that fishermen caught as bycatch from the depths of the North Atlantic off Greenland or Svalbard between 2010 and 2013.
The smallest shark was just 81 centimeters long, while the largest measured 502 centimeters.
In order to determine the age of the animals, they analyzed the lens nucleus of the sharks using the carbon-14 method.
This center of the lens of the eye is formed before the shark is born, and the proteins it contains are not renewed later.
The two smallest sharks had a striking amount of carbon-14 in the lens nucleus.
Their birth should therefore be after the early 1960s, when nuclear weapons tests spewed larger amounts of this radioactive carbon into the atmosphere.
In contrast, the lens nucleus in the third-smallest animal, which is 220 centimeters long, contained a small excess of carbon-14 from the nuclear weapons tests, so it must have celebrated its 50th birthday when it was examined in 2012.
All larger Greenland sharks, on the other hand, had normal levels of carbon-14, which is produced by cosmic rays in the atmosphere, in their lens core.
In fact, the carbon 14 clock showed an age of 335 years for a 493 centimeter long Greenland shark, while the record shark with 502 centimeters might even be 392 years old.
It was known that female bowhead sharks only have offspring when they are longer than four meters.
The researchers were now able to assign an age to the length.
Since one of the animals was probably on the verge of sexual maturity at 392 centimeters and its age was determined at 156 years, Greenland sharks apparently take at least a century and a half to reproduce.
That should also currently be a world record for vertebrates.
It is no coincidence that such Methuselahs live primarily in icy waters.
The previous record holder, a 211-year-old bowhead whale with a 120-year-old harpoon tip stuck in the blubber on its neck, was also caught off Alaska.
Due to the low temperatures, the organisms of the animals living there often run on the back burner.
So they mature later - and age more slowly.
In order to keep warm in the cold water, the animals often become particularly large.
Because the volume grows much faster than its surface, through which the animal loses heat.
The heat loss from a gram of mouse is therefore much greater than that of a gram of elephant.
Another advantage: you have fewer enemies.
&quot;A smaller animal lives more dangerously and should concentrate on having as many offspring as possible as early as possible,&quot; explains evolutionary biologist Scheuerlein.
A very large animal, on the other hand, should rather invest its resources in a long life.
