In June, Gilead was acquitted of $200 million in damages for infringing on two of Merck&#39;s patents related to Gilead&#39;s blockbuster drugs Sovaldi and Harvoni after a US judge found a pattern of wrongdoing by Merck, including of perjury and other unethical acts.
In filing the lawsuit Thursday, US District Judge Beth Labson Freeman said Gilead is entitled to waiver of costs incurred while defending the case.
Merck is trying to catch up with Gilead, which is dominating the market for a new generation of hepatitis C drugs that can cure more than 90 percent of people with the liver disease.
The case dates back to 2013 when Gilead and Merck sued each other, claiming ownership over laboratory work involving sofosbuvir, the active ingredient in Gilead&#39;s drugs.
