In order to bridge the time until the next pilgrimage to Rome for all altar boys, which is expected to be two years from now, the group of senior altar boys of St. Anna decided to prepare and carry out a pilgrimage hike lasting several days.
Various pilgrimage destinations were examined and a decision was finally made in favor of the episcopal city of Freiburg, where a special pilgrimage destination was offered this year on the occasion of the Holy Year of Mercy with the Gate of Mercy open at the Freiburg Minster.
16 minis from Bittelbronn, Gruol, Haigerloch and Heiligenzimmern set off.
The evening before, Pastor Storost sent the pilgrims out to a small celebration in St. Anna, blessed the pilgrim crosses and gave the pilgrim blessing.
From Horb, the train took you to the starting point in Villingen, where there is also a cathedral of Our Lady, and so the pilgrimage route from the cathedral began.
The individual day tours were framed in the morning and evening by a short impulse with various prayers, songs and scriptures.
But also on the way, the minis stopped again and again at field crosses, chapels or churches to sing a song together from a specially compiled pilgrim song book.
The parish homes of the local parishes were available for overnight stays.
At the stage destinations, Alexandra Burkhardt and Heidi Faller provided a tasty and invigorating dinner and breakfast.
On the second day we continued via Furtwangen to Guetenbach.
The next day, the stage to St. Peter began, which was the most strenuous stretch of the route, as the 500 meters in altitude had to be descended and then climbed again in the humid heat.
The deserved reward was a joint barbecue at the Badweiher in the evening.
After the morning impulse on the fourth day of pilgrimage in the imposing monastery church of St. Peter, we went on the final stage to Freiburg.
Visibly relieved and happy, the Minis arrived at the Freiburg Cathedral in the late afternoon and passed through the Gate of Mercy.
With a small impulse God was thanked here.
At the evening mass in the cathedral, the minis who had arrived at the pilgrimage destination were welcomed by cooperator Markus Obert.
After the service, the pilgrims could visit the sacristy and the high altar.
The next day there was still time for the Breisgau metropolis.
In the afternoon we went back to Horb by train.
In the end, all participants agreed that the days were characterized by spirituality and a strong community experience.
