Nokia 9000 Communicator: The first smartphone
E-mail and Internet in slow motion: Nokia Communicator was launched 20 years ago.
The successors dominate the world today - its manufacturer experienced a disaster.
The device weighed almost half a kilogram and was more than four times the weight of an iPhone 5.
It was thicker and bigger, so it didn&#39;t feel good in the hand either.
On the contrary, it was pretty clunky.
The built-in memory was initially eight megabytes, which would be enough for about two high-resolution selfies today.
An iPhone is now delivered with at least 16 gigabytes.
The &quot;Nokia 9000 Communicator&quot; hit the stores exactly 20 years ago, on August 15, 1996 - and it was the first smartphone.
Lovers can still buy the devices on the Internet for a few euros, but they somehow come from the stone age of the Internet age.
However, 20 years ago the Communicator was a sensation.
The Finnish mobile phone manufacturer had announced the product a few months earlier at the Cebit computer fair in Hanover as a &quot;pocket-sized office&quot;.
In fact, by the standards of the time, the new mobile phone could do a lot: SMS and e-mails could be sent and received, and the communicator could also be reached by fax.
Even websites could be accessed via an HTML browser, albeit excruciatingly slow.
A calculator was available, a digital address book and an electronic calendar.
There was a small antenna and the phone could be flipped open like a laptop.
Then there was a small keyboard and a black and white screen.
The price was quite proud: 2700 German marks, about 1400 euros.
The average retail price of a smartphone in Germany in 2015 was 392 euros.
In August 1996, nobody could have guessed that the Communicator would herald the beginning of the smartphone era.
Since then everything has changed.
The smart phones are a success story, albeit not for Nokia.
The Finns mobile phone division experienced an unprecedented disaster, was eventually sold to Microsoft and wound up.
Vendors dominate the market today, all of which came much later than Nokia.
Being online anytime and anywhere is everyday life for many people today.
In 2015 there were almost two billion smartphone users worldwide.
Around 1.4 billion devices were sold, with Samsung and Apple alone accounting for 555 million units.
Worldwide sales of the devices are around 400 billion euros.
Added to this is the thriving business of countless app providers and telecommunications groups.
An entire industry has grown up around smartphones.
The decisive breakthrough to the mass market did not come until the beginning of 2007, when Apple boss Steve Jobs announced the introduction of the iPhone at Mac World.
He promised three devices in one: a music player, a telephone and an Internet communicator, all easily operated via a touch screen.
Apple&#39;s triumphal march began, and the iPhone is still the company&#39;s most important product today.
Nokia, Motorola and Blackberry, which dominated the market, lost out.
They finally disappeared, Blackberry is struggling.
Apple and Asian suppliers like Samsung are now in charge.
The smartphone is a matter of course 20 years after its invention.
On average, every German now looks at their mobile phone 88 times a day.
&quot;We all have to learn to put down our smartphones,&quot; said Janina Kugel, who is responsible for human resources on the Siemens board.
Permanent availability is now considered both a curse and a blessing.
