Kepler measures the rotation rate of stars in the Pleiades star cluster
The latest mission with the Kepler space telescope has helped astronomers collect the most complete catalog of rotation rates among the stars of the Pleiades star cluster.
The new data help astronomers understand why stars in the star cluster rotate at different rates and how rotation periods are related to planet formation.
&quot;We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we can learn more about the relationship between a star&#39;s mass, its age and even the history of its solar system,&quot; said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech&#39;s Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena, in a press release.
The Pleiades star cluster is 445 light-years from Earth.
Formed about 125 million years ago, many stars in this star cluster are now reaching adulthood.
They are spinning the fastest now.
At peak rotation rates, these maturing stars emit large amounts of stellar winds.
As these winds travel through the stars&#39; magnetic fields, they have a dragging effect on the stars.
As a star ages, its rotation rate begins to slow.
Kepler measures each star&#39;s rotation rate by detecting the time between the appearance of a recognizable starspot -- like sunspots.
The latest catalog of rotation rates indicates that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull likens the stars to dancers, with larger stars pirouetting more slowly than smaller ones.
&quot;In the Pleiades &#39;ballet&#39; we see that slow rotors tend to be more massive, while faster rotors tend to be very bright stars,&quot; Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades star cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory to compare stellar qualities such as spin rates.
&quot;The Pleiades star cluster provides an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, younger and older,&quot; Rebull said.
There&#39;s still a lot ahead of us that we&#39;d like to learn more about, how, when, and why stars slow down their spin rates and hang up their &quot;dancing shoes,&quot; so to speak.
Rebull and her colleagues have detailed their latest analysis of the Pleiades&#39; rotation rates in three newspaper reports, forthcoming in the Astronomical Journal.
