Data theft: Hackers blackmail their ransom so perfidiously
Programmers of blackmail malware are currently targeting companies - and are successful in doing so.
According to a recent survey by malware defense specialists Malwarebytes among 540 companies in North America, Great Britain and Germany, 40 percent of the companies surveyed have been the victims of an attack with ransomware at least once, sometimes several times, in the past twelve months.
In Germany, almost 20 percent of companies have already been the target of ransomware blackmail.
40 percent of the victims willingly paid the ransoms demanded by the perpetrators in order to be able to use the attacked systems and data again.
According to observations by Malwarebytes, the perpetrators are increasingly specializing in attacks on company networks.
If they are successful there, the ransom that can potentially be extorted is significantly higher than for private users.
&quot;We are currently observing an alarmingly rapid evolution of malware,&quot; explains Malwarebytes boss Marcin Kleczynski in an interview with &quot;Welt&quot;.
In 2008, most malware programs were still designed to send advertisements.
Then the perpetrators discovered blackmail software for themselves.
Initially, private users were the target, but the switch to corporate attacks has happened alarmingly quickly in recent months.
Ransomware works according to a simple pattern: once active on a victim&#39;s computer, it looks specifically for recently modified files such as Word, Excel or database files, as well as archives of images and videos.
The ransomware encrypts these files and permanently deletes the originals.
The software then presents the extortionist&#39;s demands.
In order to get the decryption code for the files, the victims have to transfer money - usually in the form of the cryptocurrency Bitcoin.
But where the personal photo database is at stake for private users, for companies it is about sensitive customer data or project databases, without which production comes to a standstill.
The damage is correspondingly higher when ransomware strikes.
22 percent of the affected German companies reported loss of sales due to ransomware, 13 percent even had to completely interrupt business activities, and in one case people were in mortal danger.
In Germany, hospitals have already been the victims of attacks on several occasions, and their patients may be at acute risk from the loss of medical records.
&quot;We always tell the victims: Don&#39;t pay, you&#39;re only promoting the problem,&quot; explains Kleczynski.
But 80 to 90 percent of the companies that pay get their data back.
It is difficult for managers to refuse the perpetrators&#39; demands when the company is at a standstill.
The hackers, in turn, know this and do everything they can to build up a good reputation.
In a recent study, the security researchers at F-Secure examined the user interfaces and the contact with the extortionists and came to the conclusion that the perpetrators are actually trying to set up a kind of customer service in order to make more money.
They explain to their victims via chat how they can pay with Bitcoin, set up freely accessible support websites or decrypt example files for free.
And if private individuals are redeemed after paying a few hundred euros, companies sometimes have to negotiate hard and pay five-digit sums to get their data back unencrypted.
Given the potentially high and relatively risk-free profits from ransomware extortion, hackers are becoming more professional and sharing the work, explains security expert Chester Wisniewski from antivirus provider Sophos: &quot;A single person can write ransomware in about a week.&quot;
However, it is more likely that there are three or four people.
The programmers then sell their malware to the actual blackmailers in the form of a software kit.
Previous malware kits were created by purchasing the malware itself, consulting, and additional tools for a one-off, fixed price ranging from $1,000 to $10,000.
&quot;It comes with a customization tool so you can change minor configurations, looks and branding,&quot; says Wisniewski.
The blackmailers then look for other hackers to spread the newly purchased software among the victims.
We live in a service economy.
So you log into one of the underground forums, buy the set from one criminal and hire another to install the software on as many PCs as possible.
Payment is made per infected computer.
&quot;Usually, the criminals then commission spammers to spread the messages,&quot; explains Wisniewski.
The risk of ransomware is now well known to many companies who take better care of their data.
More than 50 percent of company IT managers in the Malwarebytes survey trust in being able to ward off ransomware using file backups and scanner software.
Accordingly, the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies.
&quot;If the encryption of data alone is no longer a sufficient threat for a successful extortion, the perpetrators instead threaten to publish sensitive data such as customer lists or price calculations,&quot; explains Malwarebytes boss Marcin Kleczynski.
Depending on the type of data, the potential for damage is many times higher than before.
In the future, the perpetrators could also target completely new targets in the Internet of Things.
At the Defcon hacker conference, security researchers demonstrated how they could gain control of an Internet-connected thermostat.
In the middle of winter, the activation of such a blocked heating system could well be worth a ransom for some victims.
If the perpetrators block an entire production line in a factory instead of the heating system, ransomware could also become an issue in Industry 4.0.
