A good night&#39;s sleep: tips to prevent insomnia
In the evening you toss and turn, at night you lie awake for hours, in the morning you can no longer think about sleep long before the alarm clock rings.
This is anything but relaxing.
After all, you are in good company with such problems: According to the Robert Koch Institute, around a quarter of adults have sleep disorders and more than ten percent often or permanently feel their sleep is not restful.
How do sleep problems or sleep disorders manifest themselves?
There are several forms of sleep disorders and they can have a variety of underlying causes, emphasizes Hans-Günter Weeß, board member of the German Society for Sleep Research and Sleep Medicine.
What is commonly understood by this is insomnia, i.e. a difficulty falling asleep and sleeping through the night.
Many people find sleeping through the night unsatisfactory or insufficient, says Jens Wagenknecht, a board member of the German General Practitioners Association with a practice in Varel, Lower Saxony.
What is behind sleep disorders?
The causes of insomnia are complex.
This can be due to organic, psychological or behavioral factors, but also to medication.
It is not uncommon for the sleep disorder to be an expression of another illness.
&quot;Waking up very early is common, especially in the case of depression,&quot; says Weeß.
And it may be that different factors are mutually dependent.
For example, someone who has a herniated disc can lie badly, wakes up every two to three hours and possibly starts to ponder everyday problems and worries, Weeß gives an example.
This leads to tension and sleep is no longer possible.
When should you see a doctor about insomnia?
Weeß recommends that anyone who does not sleep well for at least three nights a week over a period of one month and is impaired during the day should see a doctor.
The impairment can look very different: you are exhausted, tired, not enough sleep, have difficulty paying attention and concentrating, are easily irritable, have mood swings or physical complaints such as stomach ache or headaches.
In order to alleviate the sleep disorder, it is important to find out its causes.
Treatment options include behavioral changes, cognitive behavioral therapy or medication - classic sleeping pills only in exceptional cases and for a maximum of two weeks.
There are hardly any sleep physicians in Germany, emphasizes Prof. Ingo Fietze, head of the interdisciplinary sleep medicine center at the Charité Universitätsmedizin Berlin.
That&#39;s why you should first contact your family doctor if you have problems sleeping, advises Weeß.
He or she can use examinations to determine whether the problems have a physical cause.
Who should go to the sleep laboratory and what happens there?
Doctors recommend examinations in the sleep laboratory, for example, in the case of snoring with breathing pauses, pathological daytime tiredness, sleepwalkers or if the cause of a difficulty sleeping through the night cannot be found, explains Fietze.
You don&#39;t really need to prepare for the exam.
You should spend the day normally.
&quot;Just please don&#39;t take a nap,&quot; says Fietze.
After wiring, you go to bed at your normal time.
In addition to the electrodes on the body, you wear nasal cannula, a chest strap and a feeler on your finger.
In addition, a camera on the ceiling records the sleeping person.
How can those affected get the problems under control?
There are quite a few parameters that you can use to improve your sleep.
Weeß lists: Regular sleeping and getting up times, not lying in bed too long, not sleeping during the day, not watching TV to fall asleep, avoiding alcohol and not looking at the clock at night - then you start to calculate immediately, and that&#39;s really and not beneficial at all.
